		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text> 
						Nemo historicorum, aut aliorum fer&egrave; scriptorum, Decori est vbiq[ue] locorum obseruantior; aut viuida[e]
						pariter, seria[e]q[ue] descriptionis tenacior, qu&agrave;m Liuius. Ibiq[ue] semper maxim&egrave;, vbi 
						maxim&egrave; opus, aut vsus. Tam solerti iudicio est pra[e]ditus, et tanta discretione instructus noster 
						historicus: omni verborum,
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Livy" />
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text> 
						sententiarumq[ue] apparatu passim cultissimus.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Of the historians, or other writers generally, no-one more is more observant of the elegance of the topics, 
				or more consistent in descriptions that are both lively and serious, than Livy. And always especially so, when
				it is most needed or useful. Our historian possesses such expert judgment and is equipped with such 
				discrimination that throughout he is extremely elegant in any display of words and opinions. 
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text> 
						De fortuna, et virtute Romanoru[m], ecc&egrave; prudens, et politicus Plutarchi Liber: qui Romana[e] 
						historia[e] lectori vtilissimus; Censori, aut Critico pernecessarius est. 
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Plutarch" />
					<book title="Parallel Lives" />
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation> 
				For the fortunes and virtues of the Romans, see Plutarch's perceptive and political book, which is very useful 
				for the reader of Roman history and absolutely essential for the evaluator or critic.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Dionysius Halicarnassa[e]us Gra[e]c&egrave; de Romanorum initijs, et primis urbis temporibus, ea eleganter, 
						prudenterq[ue] tradit, qua[e] &agrave; M. Varrone, hero suo acceperat, instructissimo Polyhistore. 
						Gra[e]c&egrave; etiam de rebus Romanis optim&egrave; Polybius, Plutarchus, Dion &agrave; quo recentiora 
						quoq[ue] patefacta[e]. Et, quod ad monarchiam spectat, magis regia. Halicarnassa[e]us, Polybius, Plutarchus, Dion, 
						mea aurea specula rerum Romanarum. Sed ecc&egrave; Liuius, meum adamantinu[m] prisma: cum splendidissimis 
						mundi Luminibus, Sallustio, et Ca[e]sare; Tacito, et Suetonio; Valerio Maximo, et Frontino.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Dionysius of Halicarnassus"/>
					<person name="Marcus Terentius Varro" />
					<person name="Polybius"/>
					<person name="Plutarch" />
					<person name="Cassius Dio" />
					<person name="Sallust" />
					<person name="Julius Caesar" />
					<person name="Tacitus" />
					<person name="Suetonius" />
					<person name="Valerius Maximus" />
					<person name="Frontinus" />		
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Dionysius of Halicarnassus writes elegantly and perceptively in Greek about the beginnings of the Roman people
				and the first ages of the city, information that he received from his master Marcus Varro, that extremely 
				skillful polymath. Also in Greek about Roman matters there are Polybius, Plutarch, and Cassus Dio, who has also 
				illuminated more recent times and, when it come to a monarchy, more royal matters. Dionysius, Polybius, Plutarch 
				and Dio Cassius are my golden mirrors for Roman matters. But this is Livy, my adamantine prism, together 
				with the brightests lights of the world, Sallust and Caesar, Tacitus and Suetonius, Valerius Maximus and 
				Frontinus.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text> 
						Qu&ograve;d imprudenter Romani deos Penates, qui Troiam custodire non poterant, sibi crediderint profuturos.
						Augustinus de Ciuitate Dei. l[ibro] I. c[apite] 3. Qu&ograve;d eo tempore &AElig;neas in Italiam venerit, quo 
						Labdon iudex pra[e]sidebat Hebra[e]is. l[ibro] 18. c[apite] 19. De regibus Latii, quorum primus &AElig;neas, 
						et duodecimus Auentinus dij facti sunt. l[ibro] eod[em] c[apite] 21. An debuerit dijs Iliacis Roma committi. 
						l[ibro] 3. c[apite] 8. Qu&ograve;d Romani quosdam sibi Deos non ratione, sed adulatione instituerunt. l[ibro] 2. 
						c[apite] 15.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Augustine" />
					<person name="Aeneas"/>
					<person name="Aventinus"/>
					<person name="Labdon"/>
					<book title="De Civitate Dei" />
					<location name="Troy"/>
					<location name="Latium"/>
					<location name="Rome"/>
					<location name="Italy"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation> 
				How imprudent the Romans were in believing that they might derive any benefit from the Penates (household 
				gods), who could not protect Troy: Augustine City of God, book 1, chapter 3.
				That Aeneas came to Italy at the time when Labdon presided as judge over the Hebrews: book 18, chapter 19.
				On the kings of Latium, among whom, Aeneas, the first, and Aventinus, the twelfth, were made gods: the same
				book, chapter 21. 
				Whether Rome should be entrusted to the Trojan Gods: book 3, chapter 8. 
				That the Romans established certain of their gods through flattery, not reason: book 2, chapter 15.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
